What are graphs

What are graphs?

  • A collection of nodes and a collection of edges between nodes

What are trees? (Review)

  • Finite recursive data structures
  • Directed acyclic graphs
  • Each node has at most one parent

So, all trees are graphs, not all graphs are trees

  • So, graph algorithms will work with trees, tree algorithms might not work with all graphs
  • Have we encountered any other graphs?
  • Yes! Linked lists

So what are graphs?

  • Collections of nodes
  • And a collection of edges between nodes

Categorizing graphs

What can vary? Edges

  • The edges can be directed or undirected

  • Directed means an edge is from one node to another

  • Undirected means that there is no distinction, and an edge from X->Y implies an edge from Y->X

  • Edges can optionally have weights or other info attached to them

What can vary? Nodes

  • Just like with trees, we can attach whatever information we want to nodes
  • E.g. a number, or a color (red/black), etc.

What can vary? Additional restrictions placed on the structure of the graph

  • No cycles
  • No negative-weight cycles
  • Fully connected

Exchange rates

What can you do on graphs?

  • Depth first search
  • Breadth first search
  • Topological sort
  • Find the minimum / maximum path between two (or all) points
  • Detect cycles or negative weight cycles
  • Find bridges

How to represent graphs?

Edge list

[[0,1], [0,6], [0,8], [1,4], [1,6], [1,9], [2,4], [2,6], [3,4], [3,5],
[3,8], [4,5], [4,9], [7,8], [7,9]]

Objects

const node1 = {};
const node2 = {};
node1.neighbors = [node2];
node2.neighbors = [node1];

Adjacency lists with only one item

[1,    // node 0
 3,    //      1
 null, //      2
 2,    //      3
 3]    //      4
  • We can use these to represent how we got to a node

  • Recommended: First, assume there is no cycle, then add that functionality
  • In the above case, the answer with starting node 0 I want is [0,1,3,2]

Breadth First Search

Breadth-First Search For Trees

  • Add the starting node into the first-in-first-out queue
  • While the queue is not empty, take an item off of the queue
    • This is called visiting it. Do whatever you need with it.
    • Add all of its children into the queue

What is a queue?

  • First in, first out: array.push() combined with array.unshift()

Now you try it!

  • Implement breadth first search on a tree. Return true if an item is in the tree, false otherwise.
  • bfsContains(rootNode, valueToFind) returns a boolean

Trees vs graphs

  • Remember trees are acyclic graphs where each node has at most one parent
  • So, no need to keep track of which nodes are visited
  • But what if that’s not true?

Keeping track of visited nodes

  • Now, we can’t do pure recursion, because the solution to a sub-problem is not independent
  • Instead, keep track of visited nodes in a Set

Our state

const queue = [rootNode]
const visited = new Set();
while (queue.length > 0) {
  // do stuff
}

Sets in Javascript

a = new Set();
a.add(3);
a.has(3);
a.delete(3);

Now you try it!

  • Implement breadth-first search with a graph
  • bfsGraphContains(rootNode, valueToFind) returns a boolean

Let’s keep track of how we got somewhere

const parents = new Array(n).fill(null);
// whenever we navigate to a node n, set parents[n] = nodeWeJustCameFrom;
// then, we can iterate through this node

Now you try it!

  • Use BFS to find the shortest path to a particular node

Djikstra’s algorithm

It’s like BFS, but with positive weights

  • Used for finding the shortest path between two nodes
  • Instead of using a first-in-first-out queue, use a priority queue

Now you try it!

  • Modify the BFS implementation to use a priority queue, where the priority is the weight of the connection

Now you try it!

  • Use BFS and a depth limit to find all of the nodes that are visitable in “n” turns from a root node
